etymologies: mid 17th century; earliest use found in Thomas Blount (1618–1679), antiquary and lexicographer. From classical Latin disclūsiōn-, disclūsiō state of being separated off (2nd century a.d. in Apuleius) from disclūs-, past participial stem of disclūdere + -iō

1960s; earliest use found in American Journal Orthodontics. Apparently a remodelling of disocclusion, with loss of the second syllable perhaps by association with e.g. inclusion, exclusion, conclusion, etc. Compare earlier (in dentistry) retroclusion

definitions: Failure of opposing teeth to make contact (when the jaws are closed); an instance of this; (also) treatment aimed at producing this; = disocclusion. Compare "occlusion", "malocclusion".
